# Coordinator Operator Field Guide

Hard-won operating knowledge for the coordinator seat. Generic — applies to
any Arbiter install. Update it as you learn.

Run `arb prime` at the start of every session. Deep, situational runbooks
live in `docs/` — this guide stays short on purpose; it points there rather
than inlining everything.

**MCP first.** Every example below shows the `mcp__arbiter__*` tool call as
the primary form, with the `arb` CLI equivalent noted alongside it as a
fallback for when a session has no MCP connection. Where a CLI verb has no
MCP equivalent yet, that's called out explicitly rather than left implicit.

This preference is yours, not the operator's — they only have a terminal.
If a section here is telling the operator to do something themselves rather
than describing what you should do, give them the CLI form.

---

## 1. Role & Loop

You coordinate; the fleet executes. Core loop:

1. File an issue with crisp acceptance criteria, difficulty, and priority
   (`mcp__arbiter__task_create`; CLI: `arb issue create`).
2. Dispatch to a repo (`mcp__arbiter__worker_dispatch(task_id, repo,
   provider: "claude")`; CLI: `arb issue dispatch <id> [<repo>] --provider
   claude`).
3. Monitor — `mcp__arbiter__worker_list` (CLI: `arb worker list`), `arb
   prime` (composite session briefing, CLI-only — no single MCP
   equivalent), or a persistent event-stream monitor (`docs/monitoring.md`).
   `arb worker show <task-id>` (full worker detail + output) has **no MCP
   equivalent yet** — that's a real gap, not an oversight; fall back to the
   CLI for it.

   For **live** event streaming (not polling), see
   `runbooks/arbiter-event-monitor.md` — "**the arbiter event monitor**"
   (the `/events` tail). Distinct from this `arb prime` step and from the
   internal `monitor` component.
4. ReviewGate (pre-merge review gate) escalates for your judgment; decide,
   don't rubber-stamp (`docs/reviewgate.md`).
5. Merge and close the issue (`mcp__arbiter__task_close`; CLI: `arb issue
   close`) — or let close-on-merge handle it.

External comms (GitHub, Slack) stay in normal professional voice.

## 2. Operating Pitfalls — Quick Reference

The pitfalls that burn a coordinator most often. Check these first; each
links to the runbook with the full story.

- [ ] **Concurrency** — keep parallel issues FILE-DISJOINT. Tasks that touch
      the same file (especially a CLI verb list, command-alias map, or
      router) **will collide at merge**. Serialize those issues.
- [ ] **Config** — use `mcp__arbiter__workspace_config_get` /
      `workspace_config_set` / `workspace_config_unset` (CLI:
      `arb config get/set/unset`) only. **Never** send partial config via
      raw API PATCH — it replaces the whole map and **silently clobbers**
      siblings (`rig_paths`, tracker, merge config).
- [ ] **Deploy** — before restarting the server, check for active workers
      (`mcp__arbiter__worker_list`; CLI: `arb worker list`). **Restarting
      kills all in-flight workers and abandons their work.** See
      `docs/deploy.md`.
- [ ] **Freshness** — worktrees are cut from a freshly-fetched base branch at
      dispatch time. A pre-dispatch `git pull` of your local checkout is
      usually redundant; a **resumed** worktree can still sit on a stale base.
- [ ] **Verify** — a worker can show "running" while its subprocess is dead.
      Check the port/log, not just status. A PR marked CLEAN/MERGEABLE means
      no merge conflict, **not** an empty diff. See `docs/worktrees-and-workers.md`.
- [ ] **ReviewGate** — read the full implementer↔reviewer transcript before
      deciding. Do not assume the worst on a stalled exchange; do not
      rubber-stamp because a round ran. **Decide for yourself.**
- [ ] **Quota vs. rate-limit** — "overloaded" at low quota usage is usually an
      Anthropic-side capacity issue on the premium model, not your rate limit.
      Check the quota gauge first (`mcp__arbiter__quota_get`; CLI: `arb
      quota`). See `docs/quota-and-auth.md`.

## 3. Issue Intake — Claim & Create

When taking in new issues locally, **always set difficulty immediately
after intake**. Both intake paths create issues without prompting for
difficulty, and the field defaults to unset. Difficulty drives the model
tier and thinking budget — set it before dispatching to avoid under-scoped
work.

MCP first:

```
# Option A: Claim an existing upstream issue
mcp__arbiter__tracker_claim(ref: "42")
mcp__arbiter__task_update(id: "<id>", difficulty: <n>)

# Option B: Create a new local issue
mcp__arbiter__task_create(title: "Fix widget crash on startup", description: "...")
mcp__arbiter__task_update(id: "<id>", difficulty: <n>)
```

CLI fallback:

```bash
# Option A: Claim an existing upstream issue
arb issue claim 42
arb issue update <id> --difficulty <n>

# Option B: Create a new local issue
arb issue create "Fix widget crash on startup" --description "..."
arb issue update <id> --difficulty <n>
```

Difficulty scale (D0–D4):

```
D0 Trivial  — single-file, fully specified, no judgment (typo, config, doc edit)
D1 Simple   — localized, clear approach, light reasoning; follows existing pattern
D2 Moderate — multi-file or some design choice (default if omitted by coordinator)
D3 Hard     — cross-cutting, non-obvious design, correctness-critical
D4 Extreme  — novel architecture, deep ambiguity, may warrant multi-pass
```

## 4. File Issues Well

- **Crisp acceptance criteria** — reference real files and line numbers.
- **DIFFICULTY (D0–D4)** — drives the model + thinking budget routed to the
  worker.
- **PRIORITY (P0–P4)** — drives scheduling urgency.
- They are **orthogonal** — a P0 can be D0 (trivial config bump); a P3 can be
  D4 (hard architectural change). Do not conflate them.
- Set `target_branch` when it is not the workspace default.

Drop a one-line difficulty justification in the description so reviewers can
sanity-check your call. Both `mcp__arbiter__task_create` and `arb issue
create` accept difficulty/priority inline — no follow-up update needed at
filing time.

## 5. Concurrency Discipline

Parallel workers are good. **Keep concurrent issues FILE-DISJOINT.**

Issues that touch the same file — especially the CLI verb list,
command-alias map, or the router — **will collide at merge**. An
auto-conflict-resolver may help, but do not rely on it. Serialize those
issues: `conflicts_with` as a mutex, plus a `depends_on` chain for order
(`mcp__arbiter__dep_add`; CLI: `arb dep add`).

## 6. Freshness

Workers branch from the repo's base branch. Provisioning fetches from origin
at dispatch time, so a fresh worker always starts on current upstream — a
pre-dispatch `git pull` of your local checkout is usually redundant. A
**resumed** worktree is the exception: it can sit on an older base. Inspect
against the workspace's real base branch (forks vary — some are cut from
`main`, others from `development` or a release branch); use
`git log $(git merge-base origin/<base> HEAD)..HEAD`, not a hardcoded
`<base>..HEAD`, so a wrong guess doesn't mask real committed work. (Plain
`git` — no MCP equivalent, and none needed.)

## 7. Config Safety

Workspace config is a single JSON map stored in the database.

**NEVER** send a partial config via the raw API PATCH — it replaces the whole
map and **silently clobbers** siblings (`rig_paths`, tracker, merge config).

**Use `mcp__arbiter__workspace_config_get` / `workspace_config_set` /
`workspace_config_unset` (deep-merge) — CLI fallback: `arb config
get/set/unset`.** Never anything else.

## 8. Deploy Safely

Restarting the server **kills all in-flight workers** and abandons their
work. Before restarting or deploying:

1. Check for active workers (`mcp__arbiter__worker_list`; CLI: `arb worker
   list`).
2. If any are running, wait for them to finish — or explicitly stop them
   first (`mcp__arbiter__worker_stop`; CLI: `arb worker stop`).
3. Never restart mid-flight as a shortcut.

The full deploy runbook (release cut, `arb server deploy`, migration
gotchas, verifying a deploy actually landed) is in `docs/deploy.md` — deploy
itself is CLI/infra-only, no MCP equivalent.

## 9. Trust State, But Verify

- A worker can show "running" while its subprocess is dead — check the port
  or log, not just status.
- A PR marked CLEAN/MERGEABLE means no merge conflict, **not** an empty diff.
  Read the real `git diff origin/<base>...<branch> --stat` before calling
  work "empty" or "failed".
- Close-on-merge can miss on out-of-band merges — close the issue manually
  if it stalls (`mcp__arbiter__task_close`; CLI: `arb issue close`).
- A server restart wipes in-memory worker registrations (idle shells vanish);
  persisted issues survive.

More on diagnosing a stuck or misbehaving worker: `docs/worktrees-and-workers.md`.

## 10. ReviewGate

The pre-merge review gate. After the round cap it escalates for **your**
judgment.

Read the full implementer↔reviewer transcript before deciding. Do not assume
the worst on a stalled exchange; do not rubber-stamp because a round ran.
Decide for yourself. Edge cases (self-approval blocks, "empty branch"
verdicts that aren't actually empty, gate-failed issues with a live mergeable
PR) are in `docs/reviewgate.md`.

## 11. Watch Efficiently

Run a persistent event-stream monitor instead of polling on a fixed
interval — it wakes only on real state changes and doesn't burn tokens
re-reading context on every tick. Setup, gotchas, and the reconnect loop are
in `docs/monitoring.md` (the event stream itself is a raw HTTP connection,
not an MCP tool call — token minting stays CLI-only: `arb mcp token mint`).

## 12. Provider-Agnostic

Never hardcode model names. Route via abstract tiers:

| Tier | Use |
|------|-----|
| economy | Cheap, fast, simple tasks |
| standard | Most issues (default) |
| premium | Hard / correctness-critical work |

Plus thinking budget: `none / low / medium / high`. Resolved per adapter at
dispatch time.

**Verify CLI flags against the installed agent CLI version** — a wrong flag
crashes the worker at launch with no useful error.

Agent-CLI auth and quota gotchas (silent 401 batches, 529-vs-429 confusion)
are in `docs/quota-and-auth.md`.

## 13. Review Capability

`mcp__arbiter__worker_review` (CLI: `arb worker review <task-id>`) reviews a
PR/MR tracker-side: fetches the diff and posts findings + verdict via the
configured tracker API. The PR author needs **no** Arbiter setup.

For a ticketed review with the issue's acceptance criteria in context, prefer
a **local** task (`tracker_type: none`) with the criteria pasted in and
`pr_ref` set, then review that task — full context, zero upstream write-back.
Never claim a coworker's ticket just to get a review task; `tracker_claim` is
assignment-as-claim and risks writing back to their upstream issue.

## 14. Lanes & Merge Posture

Use **separate workspaces** for separate concerns (self-dev vs. company
repos).

| Lane | `auto_merge` | Why |
|------|-------------|-----|
| Company / shared | OFF | A human merges |
| Self-dev / experimental | ON | Safe to automate |

